    "message_type": "email",
    "scheduled_day": 3,
    "dry_run": true,
    "message_content": "Subject: Cassandra latency and ops complexity at scale\n\nHi Lin,\n\nI came across your profile and noticed Comcast is evaluating next-gen Cassandra alternatives. Given your background at DataStax and current focus on latency and operational overhead, I thought this might be relevant.\n\nWe're seeing Principal Architects like yourself tackle two persistent Cassandra pain points: p99 latencies hitting 50-200ms under load, and the compaction/GC tuning overhead that compounds as clusters scale. At Comcast's scale, that ops burden likely adds up fast.\n\nScyllaDB addresses both directly. Our shard-per-core C++ architecture eliminates JVM GC pauses entirely, delivering single-digit ms p99 latencies. On the ops side, it auto-tunes compaction and doesn't require the heap management you're familiar with from Cassandra.\n\nThe practical win: drop-in CQL compatibility means no application rewrites, but you can often consolidate 10 Cassandra nodes into 1 ScyllaDB node without touching your client code.\n\nWe've helped similar organizations complete migrations with zero downtime. I'd like to show you a quick benchmark comparison against your current infrastructure and discuss what a small POC might look like.\n\nWould you have 20 minutes next week to explore this?\n\nBest,\n[Your name]",
    "skip_reason": null
  },
