    "message_type": "email",
    "scheduled_day": 3,
    "dry_run": true,
    "message_content": "Subject: Cutting latency and ops overhead at scale\n\nHi Priya,\n\nI've been following Nubank's impressive growth across Latin America, and I imagine scaling Cassandra for 90M+ customers comes with real challenges around latency and operational complexity.\n\nWe work with infrastructure leaders managing similar scale, and there's a pattern we see: Cassandra deployments often need 10+ nodes to hit sub-50ms p99 latency targets. We've helped teams replace that with 1-2 nodes using ScyllaDB, our drop-in Cassandra replacement built in C++ instead of Java.\n\nThe main wins for ops-heavy environments like yours:\n\n1. Single-digit ms p99 latency (no JVM GC pauses eating into your SLAs)\n2. 80-90% fewer nodes needed - meaning less infrastructure to tune, patch, and manage\n\nSince you're already on Cassandra and DataStax, migration is straightforward: same CQL, same drivers, same data model. Several teams have done it with zero downtime.\n\nI'd love to show you a quick comparison specific to Nubank's workload - just 20 minutes to see where you could simplify ops and trim costs.\n\nAre you open to a brief call next week?\n\nBest,\n[Your name]",
