    "message_content": "Subject: Cutting latency and ops overhead at scale\n\nHi Wei,\n\nI've been following Grab's infrastructure work across ride, food, and payments in Southeast Asia - managing Cassandra at that scale and latency profile is no small feat.\n\nWe've worked with teams in similar positions who found that their Cassandra clusters were hitting a ceiling: p99 latencies in the 50-200ms range eating into user experience, and compaction overhead during peak write periods requiring constant operational attention.\n\nScyllaDB is built on a shard-per-core architecture (no JVM) that consistently delivers single-digit ms p99 latencies and eliminates GC pauses entirely. More importantly for your ops team: it auto-tunes internally, so no more heap tuning cycles or compaction storms derailing on-call rotations.\n\nThe kicker? Teams typically consolidate 10 Cassandra nodes down to 1 ScyllaDB node on equivalent hardware, cutting infrastructure costs by 80-90%. Drop-in compatible with your existing CQL and client libraries - no rewrites needed.\n\nGrab and other scale-up operators have migrated with zero downtime.\n\nWould a 20-minute conversation make sense to explore whether this fits your latency and operational constraints?\n\nBest,\n[Your name]",
